P. 158, l. 21. ipso . . . procurante. The keeper of an escheat is not allowed to exact ‘ procurations' as bishops and archdeacons do on their visitations. ‘Procurations’ were originally the sood necessary for the entertainment of the visitor and his following. For ‘ exeniorum' cf. Walter Map, De Nugz's Curialium, p. 224 ‘ Scriptos habebat omnes comites et barones terre sue, constituitque eis in aduentu vel mora curie sue certa exennia, quibus eos honorabat, in candelis, pane, vinoque.'
